howItWorks: |
  <h2>How this retaining wall calculator works</h2>
  <p>The calculator estimates block count from wall length, wall height, block length, and block height. It also estimates cap blocks and drainage/backfill gravel.</p>
  <h2>Important retaining wall note</h2>
  <p>Retaining walls can fail if they are not designed for drainage, soil pressure, surcharge loads, slope, frost, or height. This calculator is for basic material planning, not engineering.</p>
relatedProse: |
  <p>Need more detail on drainage stone? Use the <a href="/calculators/gravel.html">Gravel Calculator</a> to estimate gravel volume, tons, and bags.</p>
  <p>Adding a patio near the wall? The <a href="/calculators/paver.html">Paver Calculator</a> estimates pavers, base gravel, and leveling sand.</p>
  <p>Backfilling or grading nearby? The <a href="/calculators/topsoil.html">Topsoil Calculator</a> can estimate soil for surrounding areas.</p>
faq:
  - q: "How do I calculate retaining wall blocks?"
    a: "Estimate how many blocks fit in one course based on wall length and block length, then multiply by the number of courses needed for the wall height."
  - q: "How many cap blocks do I need?"
    a: "Cap blocks are usually estimated by dividing the wall length by the cap block length, then adding overage for cuts and breakage."
  - q: "Do retaining walls need drainage gravel?"
    a: "Most retaining walls need drainage gravel behind the wall to reduce water pressure. Poor drainage is a common reason walls lean, bulge, or fail."
  - q: "How much gravel do I need behind a retaining wall?"
    a: "This calculator estimates drainage and backfill gravel using wall length, gravel width, gravel height, and base depth. Project requirements can vary significantly."
  - q: "When does a retaining wall need engineering?"
    a: "Taller walls, walls on slopes, walls supporting driveways or structures, and walls with heavy surcharge loads may require engineering or permits."
  - q: "How high can I build a retaining wall myself?"
    a: "That depends on local rules, wall system, soil, drainage, slope, and load. Always check local requirements and manufacturer guidance."
  - q: "Should I add overage for retaining wall blocks?"
    a: "Yes. A 5–10% overage helps cover cuts, breakage, layout changes, and measurement differences."
  - q: "Does this calculator account for geogrid?"
    a: "No. Geogrid requirements depend on wall height, soil, loads, slope, and block system. Follow manufacturer instructions or professional guidance."
  - q: "What block size should I enter?"
    a: "Use the actual face length and height of the wall block you plan to buy. Product dimensions vary by brand and wall system."
  - q: "Is this calculator enough to design a retaining wall?"
    a: "No. It is for material planning only. Retaining wall safety depends on design, drainage, soil pressure, installation, and local requirements."
